<sect1 id="concepts">
<title>&krayon; Concepts</title>

<para>Image processing programs are centered around some concepts that
might not be immediately obvious to the new user. These concepts are
central to understanding &krayon; as well as image processing in
general. This section will explain these concepts.</para>

<sect2 id="colors">
<title>Colors</title>

<para>Computers <quote>see</quote> colors differently than the human
eye does. To a computer, everything is a number. When using a computer
to manipulate colors the human user must model colors in a way that
the computer can understand. There are several color models common to
image processing.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Indexed Color</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>The most common color model is the <quote>indexed</quote>
color. Indexed, or mapped, colors have an index from one color
representation to another. As an example, on the X Window System, the
word <quote>HotPink</quote> is mapped to the color value
<quote>#FF69B4</quote>. In a similar way, an <literal
role="extension">XPM</literal> image uses a discrete number of colors
mapped onto the full range of the system colors.</para>

<!-- TODO: Krayon does not currently have indexed color mode -->

<para>Indexed colors are useful when dealing with a small number of
colors. They become unwieldly when dealing with a large number of colors
however. Modern display hardware is capable of displaying 16 million
different colors.</para>

<!-- TODO: use DocBook acronym (or appropriate) for these color mode names -->

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>RGB Color</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>The <quote>RGB</quote> color mode can easily represent the full
range of colors on a computer monitor. RGB stands for
<quote>red</quote>, <quote>green</quote>, <quote>blue</quote>. RGB is an
additive color model,since the values for the red, green and blue
component values are added together to derive the final color. Each of
these components can have 256 different values. This results in 16
million different colors representable by the RGB model.</para>

<para>Color that comes from light behaves differently from color that
comes from pigments. When you mix red and blue paint, you get purple
paint. But when you mix red and blue light, which is what your computer
monitor is doing, you get the color magenta.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>CYMK Color</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>Printers and publishers do not use RGB or other additive color
models, since they are using pigments instead of light. They use
subtractive color models instead. If you were to break open an ink
cartridge for a color printer (please don't do this, it's messy), you
will find four different colors, cyan, magenta, and yellow. The
<quote>CYMK</quote> color model uses these three colors, plus black (the
<quote>K</quote> stands for black), to represent the same colors as the
RGB model.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>HSB Color</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>The <quote>HSB</quote> color model stands for hue, saturation and
brightness. Sometimes this model is called HSV for hue, saturation and
value. <quote>Hue</quote> describes the color on the spectrum, from red
to indigo. <quote>Saturation</quote> describes how intense the color
is. The lower the saturation value is, the duller the
hue. <quote>Brightness</quote> and value describes how bright the color
is. A color with zero brightness would be black, while one with the
maximum brightness would be very light. If saturation is zero and the
brightness set to maximum, the resulting color would be white.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Grey Color</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

<para>&krayon; also includes a <quote>Grey</quote> color mode. Grey
color ranges from black to white in shades of pure gray.</para>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="brushes">
<title>Brushes, Patterns and Krayons</title>

<para>Just as color modes are analogous to a painter's palette in
&krayon;, brushes, patterns and krayons are analogous to a painter's
brushes and palette knives. The give the <quote>shape</quote> to the
colors you paint.</para>

<para>A brush in &krayon; is the <quote>shape</quote> of the drawing
tool being used. The painting tools include the
<guilabel>Pen</guilabel>, <guilabel>Brush</guilabel>,
<guilabel>Airbrush</guilabel>, and <guilabel>Eraser</guilabel>
tools. There is a clear distinction between the
<guilabel>Brush</guilabel> tool and the selected brush.</para>

<para>Just as <quote>real life</quote> bristle brushes can be round,
flat, pointed or feathered, the brushes in &krayon; can have different
shapes. These shapes are represented by gray scale images which you can
select on the <guilabel>Sidebar</guilabel>. When you choose a round
brush with a fuzzy edge from the <guilabel>Sidebar</guilabel>, then the
lines and strokes you draw in &krayon; will be rounded with fuzzy
edges.</para>

<para>Patterns are used with the <guilabel>Stamp</guilabel> tool to
<quote>stamp</quote> patterns onto the image. Patterns come in a variety
of shapes and sizes, and they can have colors, unlike brushes which are
only grayscale.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Brushes</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="layers">
<title>Layers</title>

<para>Layers are a very useful concept in &krayon;. Newly created images
only have one layer, but you can create more.</para>

<para>You can think of them as a stack of glass sheets. When you paint
onto the top sheet of glass, none of the lower sheets are affected, yet
when you look down on the stack, you perceive only one image. Layers
work in the same way. If you create a new transparent layer on top of
your image, you can paint on that layer without worrying about it
affecting the underlying image. You can also move areas of a layer
around while the other layers are untouched.</para>

<para>You control the layers of your image through the
<guilabel>Layer</guilabel> menu and the
<guilabel>Sidebar</guilabel>. Layers can have different levels of
opacity, or transparency. You can rearrange and hide them. You can link
layers so that they can be manipulated together. And you can give your
layers names to help keep track of them. The first layer of a new image
is called <quote>background</quote> by default.</para>

<para>An especially useful layer operation is to merge layers. This
combines two or more layers into one layer. You can merge all layers,
just the visible layers, or just the linked layers. As an example, you
could do some photo touchups on a layer, and when you were satisfied
merge the layer into the original image.</para>

<screenshot>
<mediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="unfinished.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Layers</phrase></textobject>
</mediaobject>
</screenshot>

</sect2>

