<sect2 id="file-formats">
<title>File Formats</title>

<para>&krayon; uses the <literal role="extension">KRA</literal> image
file format (which stands for &krayon;) as its native file format. Most
image formats only store a <quote>flat</quote> image, meaning that only
one layer of data is saved. <literal role="extension">KRA</literal>
images are not <quote>flat</quote>, and the image layers and channels
are stored in the <literal role="extension">KRA</literal> file. It is a
good idea to save your images to the <literal
role="extension">KRA</literal> format if you plan to edit or modify them
later with &krayon;.</para>

<para>&krayon; can import from, or export to, other image file
formats. These formats include <literal role="extension">GIF</literal>,
<literal role="extension">JPEG</literal>, <literal
role="exension">PNG</literal>, <literal role="extension">PNM</literal>,
<literal role="extension">TIFF</literal>, <literal
role="extension">XPM</literal>, X Window System bitmaps, &Microsoft;
&Windows; bitmaps, encapsulated &PostScript;, and g3 fax images. The
precise list of formats that &krayon; will support depends on the &kde;
and &Qt; libraries. For example, some distributions of the &Qt; library
are not compiled to support the <literal role="exension">GIF</literal>
file format. If this is the case for you, then you would need to compile
<literal role="extension">GIF</literal> support into &Qt; in order for
&krayon; to be able to use <literal role="extension">GIF</literal>
images.</para>

<para>TODO: discussion on the various formats and how they differ from
