<sect1 id="tools">
<title>&krayon; Tools</title>

<para>Tools are the controls you use to manipulate the working
image. They include the items on the tool bars and on the sidebar. Menus
are also tools, but they will be covered in TODO: section
Commands.</para>

<sect2 id="paint-tools">
<title>Paint Tools</title>

<para>The paint tools are used to draw on the image. You can think of
them as your collection of paint brushes. You can use them to touch up
parts of an image, or to draw a new image from scratch. The differences
between the paint tools is best seen by simply using them. Drawing the
same simple figure with each of the paint tools using the same color and
brush with readily demonstrate their differences.</para>

<para>The pen tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="pencil.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Pen Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
draws sharp edged strokes. It is similar to drawing with a pen or
pencil. The pen tool will only draw with the selected color. It will not
draw in shades of the selected color. If you choose a brush with
<quote>fuzzy</quote> edges, it will still draw with sharp edges.</para>

<para>The brush tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="paintbrush.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Brush Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
draws strokes just like the pen tool, but it has <quote>fuzzy</quote>
edges. You can think of it as analogous to a a paintbrush. Although the
pen tool uses the selected color to draw with, it also uses the alpha
channel of the brush, so that it will appear to be drawing in shades of
the selected color.</para>

<para>The airbrush tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="airbrush.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Airbrush Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
draws with the selected brush but with a <quote>spray</quote> effect. It
is very similar to drawing with a real airbrush. If you click the mouse
once with the airbrush, you will get a few scattered dots. If you click
some more in the same spot, or hold the mouse button down, more dots
appear, until the shape of the brush becomes apparent. If you keep
holding the mouse button down you will eventually get a stroke identical
to the brush tool.</para>

<para>The eraser tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="eraser.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Eraser Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
works just like the brush tool, but instead of drawing onto the image
with the selected color, it erases any color on the image it
<quote>draws</quote> over. Like the brush tool, the alpha channel of the
brush is preserved.</para>

<para>The pen, brush, airbrush and eraser tools all draw using the brush
and spacing selected from the sidebar.</para>

<para>The gradient tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="gradient.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Gradient Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
allows you to fill areas with a gradient. The gradients used can be
selected and edited from the sidebar.</para>

<para>TODO: Gradient isn't working fully now, so finish this up when it
is</para>

<para>The filler tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="fill.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Filler Icon</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
fills an area with the selected color, pattern or gradient. All
contiguous areas of the same color will be filled. For example, you can
draw a blue circle with the pen tool, then use the filler tool to fill
the inside of the circle with red.</para>

</sect2>

<sect2 id="selection-tools">
<title>Selection Tools</title>

<para>The selection tools allow you to define regions in the
image. These regions, or selections, can then be moved, cut or
copied. There are different tools for selection, and each is suitable
for a different kind of region.</para>

<para>The rectangular select tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="generictool.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Rectangular Select</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
creates rectangular regions. You click the tool on one corner of the
desired region and drag to the opposite corner, to create a
rectangle.</para>

<para>The elliptical select tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="generictool.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Elliptical Select</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
creates oval or circular regions. Click on the image and drag the mouse
to create an elliptic area. If it is hard for you to get a region in the
right place, imagine a rectangular box surounding your desired oval,
then click in one corner that that rectangle and drag to the opposite
corner.</para>

<para>The polygonal select tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="generictool.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Polygonal Select</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
lets you draw irregularly shaped regions. Click the mouse with the left
button anywhere along your desired region. Move the mouse a ways along
the perimeter of the region and click the left button again. A line will
be formed joining the two points. Keeping clicking the left button
around the perimeter of your desired region. To finish you polygonal
region, click the right mouse button and the last point will be
automatically connected to the first point.</para>

<para>The contiguous select tool
<guiicon>
<inlinemediaobject>
<imageobject><imagedata fileref="generictool.png" format="PNG"/></imageobject>
<textobject><phrase>Contiguous Select</phrase></textobject>
</inlinemediaobject>
</guiicon>
is not working.</para>

